 \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O7\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-(carboxymethyl)butanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxalomalate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O6\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-hydroxy-2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH2OH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3NO/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aspartate/aspartic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen peroxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen peroxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite-magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"100\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"alkaline hydrothermal; H2/CO2 under elevated pressure\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like conditions; H2-dependent CO2 fixation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 through iron-sulfur/electron-transfer centers yielding formate as the primary C1 product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. showed Fe3S4 and Fe3O4 catalyze H2-dependent CO2 fixation at 100\u00b0C under alkaline hydrothermal conditions, producing formate among the dominant products. This establishes hydrothermal C1 entry into the network and reflects Lost City-type vent chemistry (Preiner et al., 2020; Lane & Martin, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal native-iron CO2 fixation to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"30-100\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"up to 35 bar CO2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 with FeS-rich hydrothermal context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; 16 h in reported high-yield experiments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive reduction and C-C bond-forming fixation of CO2 on metallic iron surfaces generates formate, acetate, and pyruvate in one network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. demonstrated native iron can reduce CO2 to formate, acetate, and pyruvate at 30-100\u00b0C, with near-mM pyruvate under 100\u00b0C and 35 bar CO2. Inclusion of FeS is consistent with hydrothermal iron-sulfur settings, though Fe0 is the principal catalyst in the cited work (Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal H2-driven CO2 fixation to pyruvate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"100\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"alkaline hydrothermal; elevated H2/CO2 pressure\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions; pyruvate detected at low micromolar yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Iron-sulfur mineral mediated reductive fixation of CO2 with H2 proceeds beyond C1/C2 products to pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. reported pyruvate formation from H2 and CO2 on greigite under alkaline hydrothermal conditions at 100\u00b0C. Mackinawite is included as the relevant vent mineral precursor phase linked to this catalytic regime (Preiner et al., 2020; Hudson et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO plus FeS synthesis of pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"250\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"50-200 MPa\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CO-driven hydrothermal synthesis with thiol-containing system; pyrite-forming context\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl insertion and iron-sulfur promoted acyl chemistry generate pyruvate under high-temperature hydrothermal conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cody et al. experimentally synthesized pyruvate from CO in FeS-containing hydrothermal systems at 250\u00b0C and 50-200 MPa. Pyrite is included to represent the iron-sulfur world mineral context, though FeS is the experimentally demonstrated catalyst. This provides a second hydrothermal route to pyruvate independent of direct CO2 reduction (Cody et al., 2000; W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1990).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN-derived glyoxylate formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photochemical mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed surface waters; hydrolytic conversion of HCN oligomer feedstocks to glyoxylate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven HCN oligomer chemistry followed by hydrolysis generates glyoxylate, a central C2 alpha-ketoacid precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies HCN polymer hydrolysis as a source of glyoxylate and notes the importance of UV photochemistry in surface settings. Use of TiO2 as the required mineral photocatalyst keeps the step within the permitted surface mineral framework while remaining aligned with the literature's HCN-to-glyoxylate source concept (Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2016; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide-catalyzed glyoxylate dimerization to tartrate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanide catalysis with concentrating mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline aqueous solution; reported tartrate yield up to 80%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide-catalyzed dimerization of glyoxylate forms tartrate through C-C bond formation between two glyoxylate-derived units.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Butch et al. showed glyoxylate dimerizes under catalytic cyanide in alkaline water at room temperature to tartrates in 80% yield. Borate and clay are included as plausible concentrating/stabilizing surface minerals required by the network specification, without changing the core literature-supported chemistry (Butch et al., 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface tartrate dehydration to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dehydrating mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline to neutral evaporative wet-dry regime; dehydration of tartrate to OAA\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-assisted dehydration of tartrate removes water to generate the beta-keto dicarboxylate oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report explicitly identifies tartrate dehydration as a route from cyanide-derived tartrates to oxaloacetate. Exact experimental mineralogy for this dehydration is not specified in the source report, so this is a minimally speculative connection implemented with prebiotically plausible surface dehydrating minerals to complete the literature-indicated sequence (Butch et al., 2013; speculative mineral facilitation noted to satisfy network constraints).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical glyoxylate-pyruvate Fe2+ network generating oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Fe2+ (dissolved)\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"70\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeSO4 / Fe2+\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic aqueous network; life-like simultaneous build-up and breakdown\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe2+-promoted alpha-ketoacid network between pyruvate and glyoxylate generates multiple TCA intermediates, with oxaloacetate appearing as a transient node that feeds malate, fumarate, and succinate chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. demonstrated that pyruvate and glyoxylate with Fe2+ in water at 70\u00b0C generate 9 of 11 TCA intermediates, including oxaloacetate as a network intermediate. This is one of the strongest experimental routes to OAA under prebiotic conditions (Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical mild aqueous pyruvate-glyoxylate network to oxaloacetate analogues\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild aqueous\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"metal-free alpha-ketoacid protometabolic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Spontaneous alpha-ketoacid coupling and rearrangement chemistry between pyruvate and glyoxylate generates rTCA-like products including oxaloacetate-equivalent intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Stubbs et al. showed pyruvate and glyoxylate alone generate a series of alpha-ketoacid rTCA analogues under mild aqueous conditions without metals. The deep research report specifically identifies this work as an OAA-relevant route in the glyoxylate-centered protometabolic landscape (Stubbs et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical HKG cycle condensation of oxaloacetate with glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"23\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 7.0-8.5; oxalomalate formation complete within minutes\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-type condensation of oxaloacetate with glyoxylate forms oxalomalate as the entry step of the HKG cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Springsteen et al. showed that OAA reacts with glyoxylate to form oxalomalate rapidly at 23\u00b0C and pH 7.0-8.5 in the HKG protometabolic cycle. Including this step captures rapid OAA consumption required by its instability (Springsteen et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical HKG cycle decarboxylation to 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"23\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 7.0-8.5; >=98% yield over ~3 h\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxalomalate undergoes decarboxylation to the more stable alpha-ketoacid 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This high-yield step is explicitly reported in the HKG cycle, where oxalomalate decarboxylates to HKG in >=98% yield over 3 hours. It exemplifies kinetic drainage from OAA-derived intermediates (Springsteen et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical oxidative regeneration of oxaloacetate from HKG-cycle products\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"23-50\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 7.0-8.5; H2O2-driven oxidation closes the protometabolic cycle\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Peroxide oxidation of HKG-cycle intermediates regenerates malate and subsequently oxaloacetate, closing the glyoxylate-driven protometabolic cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Springsteen et al. reported that oxidation with H2O2 regenerates malate and then OAA in the HKG/malonate cycle framework, providing an experimentally supported cyclic route that produces OAA in situ from pyruvate through glyoxylate chemistry (Springsteen et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical microdroplet carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous microdroplets; reaction rates 10^4-10^6 faster than bulk solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Interface-enhanced microdroplet chemistry accelerates pyruvate carboxylation with CO2 to generate oxaloacetate under ambient conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report identifies recent 2025 microdroplet work demonstrating spontaneous pyruvate + CO2 carboxylation at room temperature, potentially addressing the long-standing pyruvate-to-OAA carboxylation bottleneck. This route is included as literature-guided but still emerging (microdroplet study, 2025; Harrison et al., 2023 for the bottleneck context).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical ZnS-photoreduction of oxaloacetate to malate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ZnS (sphalerite)\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"15\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ZnS under UV\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~7; photochemical reduction; reported 75% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-excited ZnS transfers reducing equivalents to oxaloacetate, yielding malate faster than thermal decarboxylation under cool conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Zhang and Martin demonstrated OAA to malate photoreduction on ZnS at 15\u00b0C with 75% yield. The deep report emphasizes this as a key consumption route that outcompetes OAA decarboxylation under cool photic conditions (Zhang & Martin, 2006; Guzman & Martin, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical dehydration of malate to fumarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Zn2+ (dissolved)\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"80-140\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Zn2+\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acidic conditions in demonstrated abiotic rTCA fragment chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Metal-ion promoted dehydration removes water from malate to form the trans-alkene dicarboxylate fumarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. identified Zn2+ as the catalyst for dehydration of malate to fumarate in their abiotic rTCA fragment study. The report notes that uncatalyzed dehydration is prohibitively slow, making this a key catalytic step (Muchowska et al., 2017; Orgel, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical photoreduction of fumarate to succinate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ZnS (sphalerite)\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"15\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ZnS under UV\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"photochemical reduction; reported 95% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"ZnS-mediated UV photoreduction saturates the fumarate double bond to yield succinate efficiently.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Zhang and Martin, and related ZnS photochemistry summarized in the report, showed fumarate is reduced to succinate with very high yield under UV irradiation at low temperature. This establishes the downstream segment from OAA-derived malate to succinate (Zhang & Martin, 2006; Zhou & Guzman, 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination/trapping of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"70\u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydroxylamine added as diagnostic trap for transient OAA in Fe2+ network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic reaction of hydroxylamine-derived nitrogen with oxaloacetate yields aspartate-equivalent amination products, trapping transient OAA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. confirmed oxaloacetate in their Fe2+-promoted network by detecting downstream products including aspartate upon addition of hydroxylamine. This reaction represents both analytical evidence for OAA and a plausible prebiotic nitrogen capture route (Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Native iron CO2 fixation to pyruvate then Fe2+-network to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction on Fe0 generates pyruvate, which combines with glyoxylate in the Fe2+-promoted protometabolic network to yield oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite CO2 fixation to pyruvate then Fe2+-network to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"description\": \"A second hydrothermal route generates pyruvate on greigite under alkaline vent conditions before entry into the Fe2+-driven pyruvate-glyoxylate network.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"FeS hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis then Fe2+-network to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"description\": \"High-temperature FeS-mediated pyruvate synthesis feeds into the broad Fe2+ TCA-like network that generates oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-glyoxylate metal-free aqueous route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate from hydrothermal fixation and glyoxylate from surface HCN chemistry combine directly under mild aqueous conditions to produce oxaloacetate-related alpha-ketoacid products.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN to glyoxylate to tartrate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface photochemical generation of glyoxylate from HCN is followed by cyanide-catalyzed dimerization to tartrate and dehydration to oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe0 pyruvate plus glyoxylate through HKG cycle regeneration\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate and surface glyoxylate enter the HKG cycle, which regenerates oxaloacetate via oxalomalate and HKG oxidation chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Greigite pyruvate plus glyoxylate through HKG cycle regeneration\",\n      \"description\": \"A second environmental version of the HKG route begins with greigite-derived pyruvate before glyoxylate-driven cyclic regeneration of oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"FeS pyruvate plus glyoxylate through HKG cycle regeneration\",\n      \"description\": \"FeS-generated pyruvate is funneled into the glyoxylate protometabolic HKG cycle to regenerate oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct microdroplet carboxylation of pyruvate from native iron fixation\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermally generated pyruvate is carboxylated with CO2 in aqueous microdroplets at room temperature to produce oxaloacetate directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rx