r OAA-like and related alpha-ketoacid products, but selectivity to oxaloacetate alone is limited. The inclusion of ZnS photoreduction as a biochemical step is environmentally misplaced if not tied to a surface photic setting.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_014\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Move ZnS photochemistry to a surface or shallow photic environment\",\n        \"Specify a concrete literature-backed route from HCN to glyoxylate\",\n        \"Clarify whether rxn_009 forms OAA directly or a network containing OAA among analogues\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.74,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.89,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.91,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n      \"feedback\": \"One of the clearest surface routes to oxaloacetate. Cyanide-catalyzed glyoxylate dimerization to tartrate and tartrate dehydration to OAA align well with Butch et al. The main weakness is the upstream HCN to glyoxylate conversion, which is plausible but not specified with enough detail or agent support relative to the literature.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_005\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify hydrolysis or photochemical steps linking HCN oligomers to glyoxylate\",\n        \"Include pH and alkaline conditions for tartrate formation and dehydration explicitly\",\n        \"Discuss OAA instability and immediate downstream trapping after rxn_007\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.89\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.93,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.94,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.93,\n      \"feedback\": \"Excellent pathway. It combines a validated hydrothermal source of pyruvate with one of the strongest experimentally supported glyoxylate-driven protometabolic cycles. The HKG cycle is highly literature-aligned and appropriately treats OAA as transient and regenerated rather than accumulated. Slight reduction only because glyoxylate sourcing remains external to this pathway.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"State pH 7.0-8.5 and 23-50C explicitly for the HKG cycle\",\n        \"Clarify whether malate oxidation back to OAA is implicit within rxn_012 or requires an additional step\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.89\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.93,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.91,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"Very strong route. Greigite-derived pyruvate feeding into the HKG cycle is chemically coherent and matches the literature's convergence on glyoxylate-assisted OAA access. The route is particularly compelling as a cross-environment network story, though pyruvate yields from greigite are modest.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Mention low hydrothermal pyruvate yields and need for concentration or flux\",\n        \"Tie glyoxylate entry more explicitly to surface photochemical or cyanide chemistry\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.76,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.97