rature supports specific multistep hydrolysis/photochemical routes rather than a single abstract conversion. Third, the placement of ZnS photochemistry in the Biochemical environment is somewhat inconsistent with the literature, which situates it in shallow photic mineral settings; also, malate dehydration without Zn2+ or other catalytic support is a known bottleneck and is likely overstated in rxn_015. Fourth, rxn_017 is labeled as transamination/trapping with hydroxylamine, but the strongest literature support is diagnostic trapping of OAA by hydroxylamine to aspartate-related products rather than straightforward aminotransfer chemistry under prebiotic conditions.\\n\\nLiterature alignment is generally good and above average. The network correctly emphasizes glyoxylate-assisted OAA formation over direct bulk aqueous pyruvate carboxylation, acknowledges the carboxylation bottleneck through a separate microdroplet route, and treats OAA instability realistically. The strongest pathways are therefore the native-iron/greigite plus HKG or Fe2+ pyruvate-glyoxylate networks. Overall, this is a good network with minor-to-moderate issues; it falls short of approval at the >=0.9 overall threshold mainly because some reactions are compressed beyond what the cited literature actually demonstrates.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.93,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.92\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.91, "rxn_008": 0.93}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.92, "pathway_coherence": 0.93, "environmental_progression": 0.9, "target_achievement": 0.93, "overall_confidence": 0.92, "feedback": "Strong literature alignment. Native iron CO2 fixation to pyruvate is well supported, and Fe2+-promoted pyruvate-glyoxylate networks are among the best-supported prebiotic routes to transient oxaloacetate. Main limitation is that rxn_008 yields a mixture rather than selective oxaloacetate production, so OAA is plausibly formed but not cleanly a